4 non-negotiables for muscle growth 💪🏼

1.  Train hard (close to failure)
2.  Eat enough protein (0.7-1g/lb)
3.  Eat enough calories (~10% deficit to ~10% surplus)
4.  Do 1-3 for at least a year (be consistent)
Training for pure bodybuilding is fun because you have the freedom to be super creative. It’s just as much an art as it is a science.
Always control the negative, ESPECIALLY on the hardest reps 🔑 #PureBodybuilding

It’s technically always “triceps” and never “tricep”.

But “triceps pressdowns” sounds so wrong.

I vote that we all just keep acting like “tricep” is fine and eventually it’ll no longer be a misnomer — kind of like how dictionaries eventually updated the meaning of “literally” based on how everyone was using it.
Short-form fitness content mostly sucks right now. But it has enormous potential to elevate fitness IQ and bring in new people to the community.

Long-form fitness content has the downside of mainly appealing to people who are already super into fitness. People who are new would much rather have something explained in 30 seconds than 30 minutes, when possible.

Weekly achievement thread! 💪🏼 What’s something you did this week to get you closer to your goals? 👇🏼 Can be something big or small!
I tracked all my weights and reps this week and last week! Sometimes I slack on this. So helpful for ensuring progressive overload.
Full body splits are so criminally underrated by bodybuilders

I switched back to full body from push pull legs last week. My upcoming Pure Bodybuilding program will include a PPL split, Full Body split and UL split. Easily, by far, my best program release ever imo.

Old-school bodybuilder bros got a lot of things right.

Because of this, many will argue that scientific training studies are pointless: “Bros already knew this.”

But they always ignore the fact that the bros got a lot of things wrong too. They only count the hits, not the misses.
Training science is what helps us keep the hits and discard the misses.

This is German weightlifter Charles Ernest (via Barbell Films on IG)

We really need a study on good technique for muscle growth. One group uses perfect, controlled technique. Another group uses lots of cheating and momentum. Which group grows better?
Most science-based people would assume Group 1 would grow better, but without an actual study, this is just an assumption. I’d be very curious how the results would shake down.

I think David Laid and Simeon Panda are probably natty. They at least could be. It’s for sure within the realm of possibility given what we know about pre-steroid era bodybuilders. And we have zero concrete evidence that they have taken gear. It’d be really shitty if half the fitness community has been falsely accusing them all this time.
Combine all the natty or not videos on YouTube. How many are false alarms? I’d guess around 50%. I’d say half of people being accused of juicing are actually natty. Maybe I’m too optimistic.

But even if that number is much lower, ringing the steroids alarm on someone who is actually natty can be fairly damaging reputation-wise. Why don’t we extend the “innocent until proven guilty” principle more often in these cases?

Natty or not content is pointless.

The logic is: 

If someone is natural, and I am natural, then I can realistically achieve their physique.

But if someone is enhanced, and I am natural, then I can’t realistically achieve their physique.

This is a fallacy though. Even if you’re both natural, you will never have the same genetics and you may never achieve the same physique.

The solution: only compare yourself to your starting place. Stop comparing yourself to others.

People who make and watch fake natty content want bodybuilding to be fair. But it isn’t. Someone can be bigger and stronger than you while training less hard, less smart and less consistently. That edge can come from genetics — it doesn’t have to be steroids.
Someone can be 2 feet taller than me and not be taking growth hormone. They’re just naturally taller than me. It’s very similar with muscle mass.
It feels like 2017 with all the fake natty comments I’m getting these days. How nostalgic 😂

You’d think that after all this time people would realize that just like there are HUGE genetic differences in height, there are HUGE genetic differences in muscle mass. There is no such thing as an even playing field.

Someone at Alphaland just told me that “optimal training fell off” 😅

Is that true?
